You are processing an email (typically a LinkedIn alert, recruiter outreach, application update, or newsletter) for a specific job-seeking candidate. Do TWO things:

1. Write a concise 1-sentence human-readable summary of what the email is actually about (for the UI)
2. Extract distinct job opportunities mentioned — but ONLY ones that plausibly match this candidate's target roles

{% if candidate_target_roles %}
# Candidate context — filter extractions against this

Target roles: {{ candidate_target_roles }}
{% if candidate_current_role %}Current level / role: {{ candidate_current_role }}{% endif %}
{% if positive_keywords %}Required keywords in title (at least one must appear): {{ positive_keywords|join(", ") }}{% endif %}
{% if negative_keywords %}Forbidden keywords in title (title must NOT contain any of these): {{ negative_keywords|join(", ") }}{% endif %}

Only include listings whose role title is **plausibly in this candidate's target set AND passes the positive/negative keyword filter above**. A Director at Amazon targeting "VP/Head of Product" roles should NOT have retail hourly jobs, junior IC roles, or roles whose title contains any forbidden keyword (e.g., "engineer" if listed above). These are noise even if LinkedIn bundled them into the same alert email.

**Include** a listing if:
- Title passes the keyword filter (no forbidden keyword present; at least one required keyword present if any are required), AND
- The title matches or is a reasonable stretch for the candidate's target roles, AND
- The seniority implied by the title is within ~1 level of the candidate's current level (up or down)

**Skip** a listing if:
- Title contains ANY forbidden keyword (e.g., "engineer" when candidate has it as negative — skip even if it says "Staff Software Engineer at $220K")
- It's a different job family entirely (retail associate, warehouse, hourly shopper)
- It's a junior role clearly below the candidate's level
- It's a duplicate within this email

Mention the count of skipped listings in the summary if you skipped any, so the user knows the filter worked.
